    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">where<em> hᵥ</em>⁽⁰⁾, for <em>t</em>=0, is initialized randomly. At each time step <em>t</em>, we propagate the hidden layer feature from its neighbors to update the hidden features of a node. For <em>h</em> to reach a stable state, the parameterized function <em>f</em> must be a contraction mapping. It shrinks the distance between two points after projecting them into a latent space. But many GNN implementations are more specific and <em>f</em> does not use all the parameters on the R.H.S. So for the next three sections, let’s overview some of these GNN implementations.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5"><strong>Gated Graph Neural Network (GGNN)</strong></h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
